To factor the expression $5x^2 + 20x^4 - 30x^6$, we first identify the greatest common factor of the terms. The greatest common factor of the coefficients $5$, $20$, and $-30$ is $5$, and the greatest power of $x$ that divides all terms is $x^2$. So, we factor $5x^2$ out of each term:

\begin{align*}
5x^2 + 20x^4 - 30x^6 &= 5x^2(1 + 4x^2 - 6x^4)\\
&= \boxed{5x^2(1 + 4x^2 - 6x^4)}
\end{align*}
